        title: 'Trade Facilitation Peru 2025',
        description:
          `In 2024, foreign trade in Peru took the spotlight with major port and airport developments, alongside hosting APEC meetings. In 2025, trade facilitation must aim to ensure that both services and control for cargo and transportation align with the new infrastructure, boosting the country's competitiveness. With an optimistic outlook, we have prepared a report on the challenges and opportunities for this year.`,
        image: 'https://ifics.com.pe/thumbnails/pic1noticia.webp',
        thumbnail: 'https://ifics.com.pe/thumbnails/pic1noticia.webp',
        content: `<div><h1>Trade Facilitation Peru 2025</h1><p>Dr. Eduardo García-Godos</p><p>Lic. Ana Sofía Del Solar</p><h3>Preface</h3><p>The year 2024 brought <b>encouraging news for international trade</b>, particularly due to the launch of the Port of Chancay and the forthcoming operations at the new Jorge Chávez International Airport. While the infrastructure gap remains significant, as recently stated by the Minister of Economy, these events received extensive attention during the APEC meetings.</p><p>Nonetheless, an efficient supply chain also requires optimized services and controls (on cargo and means of transportation) based on <b>modern legislation and skilled human resources</b>.</p><p>This article provides a brief overview of <b>Peru's main progress and challenges in trade facilitation for 2025</b>.</p><div><img src="https://ifics.com.pe/noticias/public_1/public_1.webp" alt="Peru's main progress"></div><h3>Overview of Foreign Trade in Peru</h3><div><img src="https://ifics.com.pe/noticias/public_1/public_2.webp" style="max-width:1000px" alt="Overview of Foreign Trade in Peru"></div><p>Following a <b>0.55% GDP contraction in 2023</b> (INEI, 2024)...</p><p><b>Exports</b> in 2024 reached USD 74 billion, recording a <b>historic 14.6% growth</b>...</p><h3>Regional Position in Trade Facilitation</h3><p>According to the <b>2023 Global Survey on Digital and Sustainable Trade Facilitation</b>...<b>Peru ranked second in the region</b> with a score of 87.1%...</p><h4>Average Global Implementation Scores for Trade Facilitation Measures</h4><div><img style="max-width:600px" src="https://ifics.com.pe/noticias/public_1/public_3_en.webp" alt="Puntaje promedio de implementación de medidas de facilitación del comercio a nivel mundial"><p>Source: Global Survey on Digital and Sustainable Trade Facilitation, 2023.</p></div><p>Among the <b>indicators evaluated</b> — transparency, formalities, cooperation and institutional agreements, paperless trade, and crossborder paperless trade — the <b>country excelled in measures related to paperless trade</b>...</p><h4>Implementation Level of Paperless Trade Measures in Peru</h4><div><img src="https://ifics.com.pe/noticias/public_1/public_4_en.webp" style="max-width:600px" alt="Puntaje promedio de implementación de medidas de facilitación del comercio a nivel mundial"><p>Source: Global Survey on Digital and Sustainable Trade Facilitation, 2023.</p></div><p>However, <b>trade facilitation objectives and measures must go beyond those set out in the WTO Agreement</b>...</p><h3>Status of Trade Facilitation Plans</h3><p>The main public policy instruments related to trade facilitation include the National Export Strategic Plan 2025, the <b>National Competitiveness and Productivity Plan 2019-2030, and the National Port Development Plan (PNDP)</b>.</p><p>To date, the trade facilitation "agenda" has been pragmatically managed through the Multisectoral Commission for Trade Facilitation (Comufal)...</p><p>The <b>National Export Strategic Plan</b> will expire this year...</p><p>It is urgent to <b>review and update</b> the trade facilitation pillar...</p><p>The <b>National Competitiveness and Productivity Plan</b>, updated in October 2024, includes initiatives such as the <b>SMART Borders</b> model...</p><div><img src="https://ifics.com.pe/noticias/public_1/public_7.webp" style="max-width:600px" alt="Wide Image"></div><p>The PNCP also aligns with the objectives of <b>Mincetur's VUCE 2.0 Project</b>...</p><p>Last month, the updated <b>National Port Development Plan was published</b>...</p><p>However, it is crucial to <b>integrate port operations with customs functions</b>...</p><div><img src="https://ifics.com.pe/noticias/public_1/public_8.webp" style="max-width:872px" alt="Wide Image"></div><h3>Coastal Shipping, Trade Community System, and Economic Zones</h3><p>On past June, Law 32049 was enacted...allowing the participation of <b>foreign shipping companies</b>...</p><div><img src="https://ifics.com.pe/noticias/public_1/public_9.webp" style="max-width:952px" alt="Wide Image"></div><p>Additionally, in September, Law 32129 was passed...</p><p>This regulation represents important progress in <b>expanding trade facilitation</b>...</p><div><img src="https://ifics.com.pe/noticias/public_1/public_10.webp" style="max-width:600px" alt="Wide Image"></div><p>Moreover, the <b>Special Economic Zones regime</b> could undergo its most significant reform...</p><div><img src="https://ifics.com.pe/noticias/public_1/public_11.webp" style="max-width:520px" alt="Wide Image"></div><p>This project would particularly benefit the <b>Port of Chancay</b>...</p><h3>APEC Legacy</h3><p><b>Digitalization of documents and data</b> is significantly influencing crossborder trade...</p><div><img src="https://ifics.com.pe/noticias/public_1/public_12.webp" style="max-width:957px" alt="Wide Image"></div><p>As part of the activities of APEC’s Sub-Committee on Customs Procedures...</p><p>Later, in the <b>APEC Leaders' Declaration</b>, commitments were set out to promote trade facilitation...</p><h3>WTO Electronic Commerce Agreement</h3><p>Coincidentally, in July 2024, the WTO announced that a <b>stabilized text of the E-Commerce Agreement had been finalized</b>...</p><div><img src="https://ifics.com.pe/noticias/public_1/public_13_en.webp" style="max-width:600px" alt="WTO"></div><p>The stabilized text includes <b>key provisions</b> such as recognition of digital documents' validity...</p><h3>Digital Economy Partnership Agreement (DEPA)</h3><p>A major milestone has been <b>Peru’s application to join the Digital Economy Partnership Agreement (DEPA)</b>...</p><p>It also fosters single window interoperability...</p><p>This agreement complements and deepens existing provisions...</p><p>Moreover, DEPA members are committed to <b>adopting legal frameworks aligned with international standards</b>...</p><h3>Trade Standards and Digitalization</h3><p>Last year, the International Chamber of Commerce (ICC), through its Digital Standards Initiative (DSI), published...</p><p>Titled <b>"Key Trade Documents and Data Elements" (KTDDE)</b>...</p><p>According to the KTDDE, 58% of the reviewed trade documents have <b>standardized electronic versions</b>...</p><div><img src="https://ifics.com.pe/noticias/public_1/public_16.webp" style="max-width:200px" alt="Wide Image"></div><p>This report <b>analyzes 36 essential documents used in cross-border trade</b>...</p><p>It offers <b>recommendations for standardizing and digitalizing supply chains</b>...</p><p>The KTDDE significantly reinforces a “whole-ofgovernment” approach...</p></div>`,
